title: Optional outputs of the Loop Node crash the InferenceSession

body:
**Describe the bug**
Python API of InferenceSession crashes silently on inference (but I assume, there is something inside c++ core). It happens when I use Loop Node inside my ONNX model and it has optional outputs. I've marked all Loop carry dependencies as empty strings and in such case inference just crashes silently. When I set appropriate names for the Loop carry dependencies, the inference goes fine. 

**Urgency**
none

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): ubuntu 20.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): via `pip install onnxruntime-gpu`
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.10.0
- Python version: 3.8.12
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 11.5
- GPU model and memory: RTX 3090, 24245MiB

**To Reproduce**
To reproduce the behavior use the following inference code:
```python
import numpy as np
from onnxruntime import InferenceSession

def _get_pasts_input_feed(session, batch_size):
    pasts_shape = session.get_inputs()[-1].shape[:]
    pasts_shape[0] = batch_size
    pasts_shape[2] = 0

    pasts_input_feed = {}
    for inp in session.get_inputs():
        if inp.name.startswith('input_past_key_values_'):
            pasts_input_feed[inp.name] = np.zeros(pasts_shape, dtype=np.float16)

    return pasts_input_feed

model_file_path = 'loop_toy.onnx'  # or 'loop_toy_optional.onnx'. See models.tar.gz archive.
session = InferenceSession(model_file_path, providers=['CUDAExecutionProvider'])
batch_size = 16
n_steps = 30
prefix_ids = np.random.randint(0, 10, (batch_size, 20))
pasts_input_feed = _get_pasts_input_feed(session=session, batch_size=prefix_ids.shape[0])
input_feed = {
    'n_steps': np.array([n_steps], dtype=np.int64),
    'input_ids': prefix_ids,
    'temperature': np.array(0.7, dtype=np.float64),
    'top_k': np.array(50, dtype=np.int64),
    **pasts_input_feed
}

outputs = session.run(['all_output_ids'], input_feed)
output_ids = outputs[0].T

assert output_ids.shape == (batch_size, n_steps)
print('SUCCESS!')
```
Models: [models.tar.gz](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/7919071/models.tar.gz) 
There are two models: `loop_toy.onnx` and `loop_toy_optional.onnx`. Inference of the second one fails. `SUCCESS!` print is not reached.

**Expected behavior**
It's expected that the inference with the model with optional loop carry dependencies will not fail and not-ignored output will be returned.

**Additional context**
The goal I want to achieve here is to avoid unnecessary copies of the loop graph outputs from the last step. I need only scan outputs and another ones just consumes memory. If I understood the details of the Loop Node implementation, it is possible to achieve this by not returning unnecessary tensors from the loop (and I even don't use them in the downstream graph).

body:
**Describe the bug**
The onnxruntime_perf_test c++ application has two different modes of execution - sequential executor mode (default) and the parallel executor mode. By default, the application tries to exercise all the cores of the machine in both modes. However, we wanted to see the performance using single core and we used numa to bind the application to single core. Our observation was the following:

**1. With Sequential executor mode** - Though we use numa to bind the application to 1 core, it doesn't work and it ends up working as default (where it uses all cores)

**2. With Parallel executor mode** - When we use numa to bind the application to 1 core, it works with this mode and the application runs on single core.

**Urgency**
Medium.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04):  **Ubuntu 20.04.3 LTS**
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): **source**
- ONNX Runtime version: **v1.10.0**
- Python version: **3.8.10**
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): NA
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): **7.5.0**
- CUDA/cuDNN version: NA
- GPU model and memory: NA

**To Reproduce**
- **Describe steps/code to reproduce the behavior.**
Build default CPU EP (MLAS) with ONNXRT v1.10.0 release.

- **Attach the ONNX model to the issue (where applicable) to expedite investigation.**
Download the tiny_yolov2 opset8 ONNX model from here:
https://github.com/onnx/models/tree/master/vision/object_detection_segmentation/tiny-yolov2/model

**Expected behavior**
When the c++ applications is ran using sequential executor mode and if numa is used to bind it to single core, it should work as expected.

**Screenshots**

**MLAS -Sequential Executor mode:**
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/29036417/150929496-2f476765-0e55-476c-b577-3935872f79b7.png)

**MLAS - Parallel Executor Mode:**
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/29036417/150929742-60deafb3-3921-4ec4-87fc-485b06cf8c47.png)

**Note:**
we used Intel's VTune profiler Tool to get these screenshots of the core usage stats. The machine we used has 16 cores.

**Machine configuration:**
CPU(s):                          32
On-line CPU(s) list:             0-31
Thread(s) per core:              2
Core(s) per socket:              16


**Additional context**
Add any other context about the problem here. If the issue is about a particular model, please share the model details as well to facilitate debugging.

**Note:** This issue is seen only with default CPU EP. However we didn't observe similar issue while using OpenVINO EP.
so, also attaching the commands for OpenVINO EP as well, if you would like to try this out as well.

**commands to reproduce the same:**

**case 1: sequential executor mode with all cores (default case)**

**OpenVINO EP:**
./onnxruntime_perf_test  -r 1 -c 1 -v -e openvino model.onnx

**MLAS:**
./onnxruntime_perf_test  -r 1 -c 1 -v -e cpu model.onnx

**case 2: sequential executor mode with single core using numa**

numactl -m 0 --physcpubind 0 ./onnxruntime_perf_test  -r 1 -c 1 -v -e cpu model.onnx

**MLAS:**
./onnxruntime_perf_test  -r 1 -c 1 -P -v -e cpu model.onnx

numactl -m 0 --physcpubind 0 ./onnxruntime_perf_test  -r 1 -c 1 -P -v -e openvino model.onnx

title: Bump numpy from 1.19.5 to 1.21.0 in /tools/ci_build/github/linux/docker/scripts/training/ortmodule/stage2
body:
Bumps [numpy](https://github.com/numpy/numpy) from 1.19.5 to 1.21.0.
Release notes

Sourced from numpy's releases.

v1.21.0

NumPy 1.21.0 Release Notes

The NumPy 1.21.0 release highlights are

  • continued SIMD work covering more functions and platforms,
  • initial work on the new dtype infrastructure and casting,
  • universal2 wheels for Python 3.8 and Python 3.9 on Mac,
  • improved documentation,
  • improved annotations,
  • new PCG64DXSM bitgenerator for random numbers.

In addition there are the usual large number of bug fixes and other improvements.

The Python versions supported for this release are 3.7-3.9. Official support for Python 3.10 will be added when it is released.

:warning: Warning: there are unresolved problems compiling NumPy 1.21.0 with gcc-11.1 .

  • Optimization level -O3 results in many wrong warnings when running the tests.
  • On some hardware NumPy will hang in an infinite loop.

New functions

Clip's range is larger than QuantizeLinear's, if it is, drop the Clip.

The range of QuantizeLinear is deducted according to following formulas:
* For int8_t zero_point: scale * [-128 - zero_point, 127 - zero_point]
* For uint8_t zero_point: scale * [0- zero_point, 255 - zero_point]
